00:00:27.484 --> 00:00:28.770
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Today is--

00:00:28.770 --> 00:00:30.960
it's not exactly a
midpoint of the course,

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:35.940
but it is a transition
lecture between

00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:40.080
these macro financial models
with micro underpinnings.

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:42.990
Today we're going to go
through the measurement,

00:00:42.990 --> 00:00:49.560
and then in subsequent
lectures, focus on testing

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:51.295
for the micro underpinnings.

00:00:51.295 --> 00:00:53.420
I mean, everything is
connected to everything else.

00:00:56.130 --> 00:00:56.940
There's a quote--

00:00:56.940 --> 00:00:59.550
I don't know, many of you
may be familiar with it.

00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:01.410
It's really quite good.

00:01:01.410 --> 00:01:03.950
Lord Kelvin.

00:01:03.950 --> 00:01:06.540
In physical science,
the first essential step

00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:10.500
in the direction of
learning any subject

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:12.840
is define the principles
of numerical reckoning

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:14.790
and practicable
methods for measuring

00:01:14.790 --> 00:01:18.090
some quality connected with it.

00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:20.730
I often say that
you can measure--

00:01:20.730 --> 00:01:23.460
when you can measure what you're
speaking about and express it

00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:27.130
in numbers, you know
something about it,

00:01:27.130 --> 00:01:29.490
but when you cannot measure
it, you cannot express it

00:01:29.490 --> 00:01:33.540
in numbers, your knowledge is
of a meager and unsatisfactory

00:01:33.540 --> 00:01:35.700
kind.

00:01:35.700 --> 00:01:37.440
It may be the
beginning of knowledge,

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:40.260
but you have scarcely
in your thoughts

00:01:40.260 --> 00:01:43.380
advanced to the
stage of science,

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:47.310
whatever that matter may be.

00:01:47.310 --> 00:01:50.340
So of course, today we're going
to talk about measurement,

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:52.660
and this is not an
economics quote.

00:01:52.660 --> 00:02:00.510
This is a little more related
to both economics and impact

00:02:00.510 --> 00:02:01.440
evaluation.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:03.390
It's Bill Gates.

00:02:03.390 --> 00:02:05.205
He's talking about
the steam engine.

00:02:05.205 --> 00:02:10.229
In his book I think he must have
read on the most powerful idea

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:14.790
in the world, which is
about measuring the energy

00:02:14.790 --> 00:02:19.130
output of engines with
this my micrometer.

00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:26.690
The point-- he's
quoting Mr. Rosen--

00:02:26.690 --> 00:02:28.920
is to see incremental
design changes

00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:30.480
that led to improvement--

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:33.690
mainly what you want, higher
power and less consumption

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:35.510
of the coal.

00:02:35.510 --> 00:02:39.710
And it was this interaction
between experimenting, trying

00:02:39.710 --> 00:02:43.400
things, measuring
precisely given the goal

00:02:43.400 --> 00:02:46.040
and then innovating
some more that

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:52.250
led to this high-powered steam
engine which revolutionized

00:02:52.250 --> 00:02:55.370
the world, essentially.

00:02:55.370 --> 00:02:57.230
So he's saying he's
struck how important it

00:02:57.230 --> 00:03:01.370
is to measure-- to improve
the human condition

00:03:01.370 --> 00:03:05.060
and how incredible the progress
could be if you set a goal

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:08.090
and measure it.

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:11.990
But then he goes on
to say that he is also

00:03:11.990 --> 00:03:14.030
amazed how little
this is actually done

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:17.020
and how hard it is to
do it to get it right.

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:19.460
He gives an example
of foreign aid,

00:03:19.460 --> 00:03:23.510
just measuring the dollars,
say, that flow rather than

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:26.270
the underlying impact
that it may or may not

00:03:26.270 --> 00:03:31.375
have on household business
or country welfare.

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:36.870
So the type of measurements
that are needed or those that

00:03:36.870 --> 00:03:40.275
allow us to assess
performance and gauge impact.

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:49.640
So this is the end of
what Bill Gates was saying

00:03:49.640 --> 00:03:51.590
and the rest is
something I want to say.

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:56.520
Measurement is
tricky in the sense

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:59.730
that he's really not saying
just go out and measure

00:03:59.730 --> 00:04:04.650
anything you want to
consistent with the goal.

00:04:04.650 --> 00:04:09.570
For a while the Gates Foundation
was promoting savings accounts,

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:12.690
having poor people have
access to savings account

00:04:12.690 --> 00:04:17.610
as a kind of panacea,
and indeed, wanted

00:04:17.610 --> 00:04:19.800
to measure the
number of households

00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:24.150
out there now who have
them and track improvement.

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:31.320
And there's a new world survey
done by the Gallup Foundation--

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:33.390
Gallup people who do
the polls, actually,

00:04:33.390 --> 00:04:36.360
have survey
techniques worldwide.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:41.840
But of course, from
our perspective,

00:04:41.840 --> 00:04:44.690
just having a savings account
may not accomplish much.

00:04:44.690 --> 00:04:46.700
It's not a kind of
measurement that's really

00:04:46.700 --> 00:04:49.070
assessing the impact on people.

00:04:49.070 --> 00:04:52.940
You'd like to know what impact
it's having on welfare--

00:04:52.940 --> 00:04:54.920
that is to say on
actually using it

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:58.520
or better ability to smooth
consumption or finance

00:04:58.520 --> 00:05:00.980
investments and so on.

00:05:03.850 --> 00:05:05.250
Well fortunately
in economics, we

00:05:05.250 --> 00:05:10.440
have one set of measurement
tools that are common,

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:14.070
and they're also consistent
with the theme of the lectures--

00:05:14.070 --> 00:05:17.160
namely there is measurement
at the individual household

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:21.300
level that's also
consistent with measurement

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:24.780
of the flow of funds across
countries and everything

00:05:24.780 --> 00:05:26.290
in between.

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:31.560
And what I'm going to
try to go through today

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:37.380
but here's a quick summary of
it is what these tools are.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:43.070
Basically you start with
the financial accounts

00:05:43.070 --> 00:05:45.440
for a household or a firm.

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:48.030
So that would be the balance
sheet, the income statement,

00:05:48.030 --> 00:05:51.290
and the statement of cash flow.

00:05:51.290 --> 00:05:55.430
You may associate that language
with corporate financial

00:05:55.430 --> 00:06:00.530
accounting and wonder
perhaps about its relevance,

00:06:00.530 --> 00:06:03.650
but they are the
benchmark standards

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:07.160
and they can be applied to
households and especially

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:09.050
to households running
businesses, which

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:11.880
is the typical enterprise
in developing countries.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:20.130
So I'll show you in a moment
exactly how this can be done.

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:23.550
What use can you
make of these things?

00:06:23.550 --> 00:06:26.670
Again, I'm going to try to
buttress my case that it's not

00:06:26.670 --> 00:06:28.560
just measurement for
the sake of measurement,

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:33.130
but actually that you can
use these measurements.

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:37.380
So in this case, we'll
draw a distinction between

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:42.670
productivity and the return
on assets versus liquidity,

00:06:42.670 --> 00:06:45.870
some distinction you could
not make if you were not

00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:50.610
clear-headed as in applying
these financial accounts--

00:06:50.610 --> 00:06:53.790
or at least it would be
quite easy to make mistakes.

00:06:59.600 --> 00:07:05.410
And show how-- where
wealth is coming from

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:08.020
and how wealth
changes over time.

00:07:08.020 --> 00:07:11.620
At the household level that
gets you into poverty dynamics,

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:15.940
you can start thinking about the
mechanics that underlie changes

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:16.960
in inequality.

00:07:22.010 --> 00:07:25.520
And again, in an
application, take a look

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:31.840
at how households are making
a distinction, apparently,

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:35.200
between savings rates
and productivity

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:38.420
in terms of what they do
in their own investment.

00:07:38.420 --> 00:07:42.130
I think you've seen in
the recitation section

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:44.590
sort of a precursor of
this in terms of the Thai

00:07:44.590 --> 00:07:47.660
data and some case studies.

00:07:47.660 --> 00:07:50.230
So in some sense, we're going
to go back to the basics

00:07:50.230 --> 00:07:53.360
and talk about the
financial accounts,

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:59.830
but at least you have
a motivation already

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:04.050
for what households are doing.

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:07.560
Then we can aggregate
up from households--

00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:13.010
say all households in a
village and create something

00:08:13.010 --> 00:08:14.510
like the national
income accounts,

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:17.090
except they're not at
the national level,

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:19.580
they're village income accounts.

00:08:19.580 --> 00:08:26.450
But we have the standard savings
and investment, GDP numbers,

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:31.850
and indeed, we get balance
of payments at the village

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:35.929
level or regional
level just so you

00:08:35.929 --> 00:08:39.500
can see what's going on within
the country, not just of

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:41.280
the country relative to other--

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:44.330
and again, you've seen this
come up in the lectures--

00:08:44.330 --> 00:08:47.840
China, provincial-level
China, at the national level

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:51.920
relative to the
rest of the world,

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:55.340
flows across sectors that
differ in obstacles to trade.

00:08:59.980 --> 00:09:05.350
And finally, we'll get to the
flow of funds accounting, which

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:07.690
I like to think of
as the nuts and bolts

00:09:07.690 --> 00:09:10.550
of the financial system
actually measured.

00:09:10.550 --> 00:09:13.330
So you don't just
have to imagine

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:16.390
what's going on in
the country over time

00:09:16.390 --> 00:09:19.030
in response to shocks,
you can actually

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:21.152
see it in the measurement.

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:31.820
So first paper up.

00:09:31.820 --> 00:09:32.720
Not going to work?

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.910
Let's not cut off too
much, maybe it's all right.

00:09:39.910 --> 00:09:50.000
Is to create-- well, I'm
just not fast enough.

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:57.160
Create the balance
sheet, income statement,

00:09:57.160 --> 00:10:00.300
and statement of cash
flow for these households

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:03.720
in order to make the
distinction between productivity

00:10:03.720 --> 00:10:05.530
and liquidity.

00:10:05.530 --> 00:10:12.330
So this is a quote from
Deaton that I ask often show.

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:14.580
The only way to
obtain these measures

00:10:14.580 --> 00:10:16.680
is by imposing an
accounting framework

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.950
on the data, painstakingly
construct estimates

00:10:19.950 --> 00:10:21.870
from myriad responses
to questions

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:25.470
about the specific components
that contribute to the total.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:29.370
So actually, there's
a computer code

00:10:29.370 --> 00:10:34.410
that's you know 18 to 20
pages single-line code,

00:10:34.410 --> 00:10:36.880
and it operates
on the Thai data.

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:40.830
It, of course, searches
over all the questions

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:42.300
in the questionnaire
in order to be

00:10:42.300 --> 00:10:44.940
able to extract the
key variables that

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:47.910
are needed line
by line to create

00:10:47.910 --> 00:10:49.500
these financial accounts.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:51.990
We didn't begin with
the financial accounts.

00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:55.530
I wish we had, because
then certain instances,

00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:58.290
it would have helped
us measure better.

00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:02.460
This was something
we came to afterwards

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:04.470
when we were just struggling
with a simple idea

00:11:04.470 --> 00:11:07.920
of what do we really
mean by income?

00:11:07.920 --> 00:11:09.300
Something very basic.

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:12.490
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] more
like 100 page, you think.

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:13.740
ROBERT TOWNSEND: That's a lot.

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:15.750
AUDIENCE: And the way that
you look at it is initial.

00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:16.667
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:11:16.667 --> 00:11:19.470
Version 1, version 2.

00:11:19.470 --> 00:11:21.600
OK.

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:22.980
So what are the
problems when you

00:11:22.980 --> 00:11:25.740
have these high frequency
monthly data or to some degree

00:11:25.740 --> 00:11:27.540
even annual data?

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:29.760
There is a difference
in timing between, say,

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:33.540
when inputs are purchased and
when their outputs are sold.

00:11:33.540 --> 00:11:37.380
If you think about farmers,
they only sell at harvest time

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:39.930
and they're using
inputs along the way.

00:11:42.810 --> 00:11:47.790
It's true for businesses, too,
who don't sell instantaneously.

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:51.150
They have to acquire inputs
to produce something or buy

00:11:51.150 --> 00:11:55.455
goods for inventory to stock,
and then subsequently sell.

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:02.850
We are worried about
liquidity, on the other hand.

00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:05.090
So since smoothing
of consumption,

00:12:05.090 --> 00:12:07.010
protection of
investment from cash

00:12:07.010 --> 00:12:10.440
flow, financing a
budget deficits.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:14.600
So we want to make
distinction between cash flow

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:20.090
in terms of liquidity and kind
of the overall performance.

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:24.710
The key idea with performance
is an accrual notion

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:28.250
of accounting, which
is simple to say--

00:12:28.250 --> 00:12:31.220
mainly do not book
or subtract expenses

00:12:31.220 --> 00:12:33.080
until the output is sold.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:35.300
It's the idea of
corporate finance--

00:12:35.300 --> 00:12:38.330
you have projects,
not occupations.

00:12:38.330 --> 00:12:39.680
You buy assets.

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:44.420
You have an idea, you need to
fund it, you buy equipment,

00:12:44.420 --> 00:12:48.830
and you don't expect
a return right away.

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:53.780
So for the short-run, you
have lots of negative profits,

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:56.600
but it's just a
cash outflow, so you

00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:59.360
wait till you can get
the big picture, which

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:04.260
is when you get the revenue then
you subtract off the inputs.

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:06.270
But financing the
inputs along the way,

00:13:06.270 --> 00:13:08.700
that's a liquidity issue.

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:10.890
And indeed, if
you're running out,

00:13:10.890 --> 00:13:15.840
you may as not invest even
though your underlying project

00:13:15.840 --> 00:13:17.970
or idea is quite successful.

00:13:22.820 --> 00:13:25.730
So we go to the
financial accounts.

00:13:25.730 --> 00:13:33.090
Now viewing households as firms,
we have to draw some parallels.

00:13:33.090 --> 00:13:36.660
Assets are kind of easy to think
about both on the household

00:13:36.660 --> 00:13:42.930
side and on the firm side.

00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:47.740
Households have debt just
like firms have liabilities,

00:13:47.740 --> 00:13:54.120
so those are straightforward
parallel concepts.

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:56.950
When you think
about wealth, wealth

00:13:56.950 --> 00:14:00.415
is really net worth
on the household side.

00:14:03.010 --> 00:14:06.750
The language for firms
is something like equity.

00:14:06.750 --> 00:14:13.220
It's the amount of the owners'
investment in the enterprise

00:14:13.220 --> 00:14:18.600
that's built up over
time that is not

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:21.980
as different from the fact
that some of the equipment

00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:24.210
gets owned by
outsiders who financed

00:14:24.210 --> 00:14:25.940
the project by lending.

00:14:29.670 --> 00:14:31.860
What is the sources
of this wealth?

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:36.180
Well basically savings,
like retained earnings.

00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:40.050
Savings for households, retained
earnings for businesses.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:44.280
That part of the profits that
you put back into the business.

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:48.210
But also potentially
contributed capital

00:14:48.210 --> 00:14:50.160
which I'll come to in a minute.

00:14:50.160 --> 00:14:54.840
This is this may strike you
as odd at first, I'm not sure.

00:14:54.840 --> 00:14:56.640
Consumption on
the household side

00:14:56.640 --> 00:15:00.200
is the same as dividends
on the firm side.

00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:03.620
So the consumption
we think we know,

00:15:03.620 --> 00:15:09.800
but dividends is
like a firm paying

00:15:09.800 --> 00:15:13.460
either the inside owners
or outside investors part

00:15:13.460 --> 00:15:14.420
of the return stream.

00:15:14.420 --> 00:15:17.870
So that stuff isn't going
into the firm anymore,

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:20.060
it's not retained earnings.

00:15:20.060 --> 00:15:26.220
It's kind of the fruit
that you get to enjoy.

00:15:26.220 --> 00:15:31.350
This is also a bit of a
stretch and can be problematic.

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:34.800
Incoming gifts on
the household side,

00:15:34.800 --> 00:15:38.550
what do we do with them
in the financial accounts?

00:15:38.550 --> 00:15:43.350
Gifts aren't really
income in some sense--

00:15:43.350 --> 00:15:45.120
in the corporate
financial sense.

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:48.990
Because income is a
return stream of projects,

00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:54.570
but gifts, that's just
something somebody gave you.

00:15:54.570 --> 00:15:57.870
Well, so we ended up thinking
about gifts as financing.

00:15:57.870 --> 00:16:00.830
So the idea is, someone
gives you a gift,

00:16:00.830 --> 00:16:05.160
you have some implicit
idea of reciprocity.

00:16:05.160 --> 00:16:08.640
So they're in effect
helping your enterprise,

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:12.950
they're investing
in your enterprise

00:16:12.950 --> 00:16:15.800
even though the contract
may not be nearly as formal

00:16:15.800 --> 00:16:18.765
as, say, an equity arrangement.

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:23.720
And finally, the household
budget constraint

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:28.680
is like the firm
cash flow constraint.

00:16:28.680 --> 00:16:31.740
So again, we can
therefore distinguish

00:16:31.740 --> 00:16:34.200
assets versus wealth.

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:36.750
Note how easy it would be
to make a mistake there.

00:16:36.750 --> 00:16:37.860
Isn't that the same thing?

00:16:37.860 --> 00:16:38.400
No.

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:44.270
Remember, the liabilities
get subtracted from assets

00:16:44.270 --> 00:16:46.460
to create, quote,
wealth or net worth.

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:49.670
Accrual versus cash flow
I've said often enough.

00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:52.760
Savings as a budget
surplus as in cash flow--

00:16:52.760 --> 00:16:57.050
so you had more coming in in
revenue than you had outflows

00:16:57.050 --> 00:17:02.780
in terms of expenses versus a
different notion of savings,

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:05.839
and that's savings as in
wealth accumulation, that's

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:13.670
where do you put the increasing
wealth that you're acquiring?

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:15.619
That's more like a
portfolio problem.

00:17:17.958 --> 00:17:19.500
And therefore, we
need to distinguish

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:22.401
liquidity management
from asset management.

00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:27.900
So quick review.

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:30.900
By the way, I'm really
going to struggle today

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:35.460
to make sure you don't just
sort of pass out on me.

00:17:35.460 --> 00:17:37.650
Because accounting
has a reputation

00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:40.530
as being really
boring, and it is true

00:17:40.530 --> 00:17:43.710
that it gets more
and more tedious.

00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:45.690
And so you kind
of like tune out,

00:17:45.690 --> 00:17:51.270
like OK, I'll tolerate today.

00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:54.100
But no, you'll
discover that when

00:17:54.100 --> 00:17:57.310
you start doing your research,
whether it's looking at data

00:17:57.310 --> 00:18:01.780
from surveys or gathering
data or trying to do--

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:05.313
and then you'll come back and
you'll be much more interested

00:18:05.313 --> 00:18:05.980
in these things.

00:18:05.980 --> 00:18:10.120
So the spirit with which I give
the lecture today is not the

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:13.660
bore you with the details,
even though at times it

00:18:13.660 --> 00:18:17.560
will be tempting, because once
you've invested in this stuff,

00:18:17.560 --> 00:18:19.880
you want to share
that knowledge.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:24.160
But rather, to give you a
reader's guide or viewer's

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:26.170
guide of what the
key concepts are

00:18:26.170 --> 00:18:27.980
and how things fit together.

00:18:27.980 --> 00:18:31.910
So that latter thing is what
I want you to take away.

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:36.100
So here is a typical
balance sheet.

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:40.120
You've got assets and
you've got liabilities.

00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:43.670
The bottom line
has to be the same.

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:45.920
Now how does that happen?

00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:47.980
Well, you really
subtract liabilities

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:52.820
off from the assets, and
hopefully assets are larger,

00:18:52.820 --> 00:18:57.390
so the residual is basically
equity or net worth, OK?

00:18:57.390 --> 00:18:59.100
And then this is
just an enumeration

00:18:59.100 --> 00:19:01.530
of different kinds
of assets, which

00:19:01.530 --> 00:19:05.700
include financial and
trade credit and so on as

00:19:05.700 --> 00:19:10.530
well as if-- lending as well
as your real physical fixed

00:19:10.530 --> 00:19:17.950
assets, and liabilities are
kind of obvious, and so on.

00:19:17.950 --> 00:19:25.710
So now let's get
into some cases here.

00:19:25.710 --> 00:19:28.320
The Living Standards
Measurement Survey

00:19:28.320 --> 00:19:34.810
makes a mistake if you want
to think of it that way.

00:19:34.810 --> 00:19:38.200
They ask about inputs used over
a specified cropping season

00:19:38.200 --> 00:19:39.115
and the amount spent.

00:19:42.470 --> 00:19:45.150
And implicitly
they're equating them,

00:19:45.150 --> 00:19:48.170
but they don't have to
be equal to each other.

00:19:48.170 --> 00:19:52.070
For one thing, you could be
using inputs in your farm

00:19:52.070 --> 00:19:55.280
that you acquired previously--
especially with monthly data,

00:19:55.280 --> 00:20:00.800
it's likely you have some
kind of input inventory.

00:20:00.800 --> 00:20:04.430
And for that matter,
you could spend money

00:20:04.430 --> 00:20:06.890
and buy inputs but not
actually put them on the field.

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:19.370
And the same thing happens on
the output side, essentially.

00:20:19.370 --> 00:20:20.090
What do we do?

00:20:20.090 --> 00:20:23.660
Fortunately in the Thai
survey, we actually

00:20:23.660 --> 00:20:26.480
keep track of both
inputs required

00:20:26.480 --> 00:20:28.550
since the previous
interview as well as

00:20:28.550 --> 00:20:32.080
the actual use, both value
and quantity of inputs.

00:20:32.080 --> 00:20:35.555
So we have this input
inventory account.

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:43.928
And revenues I say here,
but don't dwell on it.

00:20:43.928 --> 00:20:45.720
So what do you do when
you have the output?

00:20:45.720 --> 00:20:48.320
Well, you could store
it or you could sell it

00:20:48.320 --> 00:20:49.820
or you could eat it.

00:20:49.820 --> 00:20:52.460
So you kind of have to
create an output account.

00:20:52.460 --> 00:20:57.710
We act as if output is sold
at the time of harvest just

00:20:57.710 --> 00:21:01.190
to put an accurate value on
it, but when, in fact, they

00:21:01.190 --> 00:21:05.960
don't sell all of it or they
eat some and store some,

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:10.290
then we create another sort
of output inventory account.

00:21:10.290 --> 00:21:14.240
So in high frequency data,
this sort of inventory

00:21:14.240 --> 00:21:16.753
that your mind might
glaze over when

00:21:16.753 --> 00:21:18.170
you look at a
financial statement,

00:21:18.170 --> 00:21:24.250
inventory may be a really
key smoothing device.

00:21:24.250 --> 00:21:27.730
And at the risk of
getting carried away,

00:21:27.730 --> 00:21:31.270
there's something called
work-in-progress inventory,

00:21:31.270 --> 00:21:34.060
and that happens when
you're using this accrual

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:35.950
notion of accounting
where you don't

00:21:35.950 --> 00:21:39.010
want to subtract something
off as an expense yet.

00:21:39.010 --> 00:21:41.080
If you don't subtract
it off as an expense,

00:21:41.080 --> 00:21:44.120
then it's not on the
income statement.

00:21:44.120 --> 00:21:46.240
Well where the heck is it?

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:49.120
Well basically,
you act like you've

00:21:49.120 --> 00:21:52.750
created an inventory
of something,

00:21:52.750 --> 00:21:54.880
like buying an asset.

00:21:54.880 --> 00:21:57.400
So all the fertilizer that
you've put on the land

00:21:57.400 --> 00:21:59.500
and all of that stuff
in the accrual notion

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:03.010
is work-in-progress inventory,
it's producing the crop.

00:22:06.970 --> 00:22:07.770
Yep?

00:22:07.770 --> 00:22:10.200
AUDIENCE: So how do you--

00:22:10.200 --> 00:22:13.150
literally-- so how
do you kind of--

00:22:13.150 --> 00:22:16.380
so I'm assuming
that in your survey

00:22:16.380 --> 00:22:18.460
you ask kind of a
simpler question,

00:22:18.460 --> 00:22:20.593
like just count
assets and name--

00:22:20.593 --> 00:22:21.510
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:22:21.510 --> 00:22:22.908
AUDIENCE: --expenses and what--

00:22:22.908 --> 00:22:23.950
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Exactly.

00:22:23.950 --> 00:22:26.340
AUDIENCE: --like that.

00:22:26.340 --> 00:22:30.900
How can you be sure that
your classification kind of

00:22:30.900 --> 00:22:34.560
is what it is and it's in
the mind of the households?

00:22:34.560 --> 00:22:40.410
So like I understand sort of
the asset versus wealth thing

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:44.070
and so on, but when you go into
this like inventories and stuff

00:22:44.070 --> 00:22:44.867
like that, how--

00:22:44.867 --> 00:22:46.200
ROBERT TOWNSEND: We create that.

00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:47.930
We don't ask the
household what they're

00:22:47.930 --> 00:22:50.430
a work-in-progress inventory is.

00:22:50.430 --> 00:22:52.710
We have that as a
conceptual category

00:22:52.710 --> 00:22:54.990
as measured from
other variables,

00:22:54.990 --> 00:22:58.242
like what did they buy,
not yet put on the land.

00:22:58.242 --> 00:23:00.810
AUDIENCE: Would you think
it's interesting to go

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:04.393
see whether that maps
in into some sort of--

00:23:04.393 --> 00:23:05.310
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:23:05.310 --> 00:23:05.880
AUDIENCE: --way--

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:07.755
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So
Chris Woodruff had done--

00:23:07.755 --> 00:23:10.710
the inventory thing is the
hardest thing to get right.

00:23:13.240 --> 00:23:15.130
And in fact, when
you think about it,

00:23:15.130 --> 00:23:18.250
you buy maybe
inputs at one price

00:23:18.250 --> 00:23:19.580
and you sell them in another.

00:23:19.580 --> 00:23:21.100
So you can have--

00:23:21.100 --> 00:23:24.580
or-- so you can have
capital gains and losses

00:23:24.580 --> 00:23:27.370
on the inventory account.

00:23:27.370 --> 00:23:28.180
AUDIENCE: Yeah--

00:23:28.180 --> 00:23:30.570
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
And-- and so yeah.

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:33.210
So what Chris has
done is actually--

00:23:33.210 --> 00:23:36.040
he wrote a paper called--

00:23:36.040 --> 00:23:38.320
and we take the
opposite point of view,

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:42.140
but his is, how is
the sausage made?

00:23:42.140 --> 00:23:44.090
Or don't ask what's
in the sausage.

00:23:44.090 --> 00:23:48.540
So he just asks households
basically what their income is,

00:23:48.540 --> 00:23:52.690
and the view there is
that somehow they're

00:23:52.690 --> 00:23:57.070
going to do better than asking
all these detailed questions.

00:23:57.070 --> 00:24:00.010
We think it's better to
ask the detailed questions

00:24:00.010 --> 00:24:03.700
and then construct the income,
but you can certainly--

00:24:03.700 --> 00:24:05.800
and we didn't do enough of this.

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:06.940
So yes.

00:24:06.940 --> 00:24:12.050
You should compare the answers
of the households to so--

00:24:12.050 --> 00:24:15.130
and do the households have
in mind some liquidity notion

00:24:15.130 --> 00:24:18.010
of income or do they have
in mind some sort of rate

00:24:18.010 --> 00:24:21.010
of return calculation when you
ask them what their income is

00:24:21.010 --> 00:24:23.480
in a given year?

00:24:23.480 --> 00:24:25.460
AUDIENCE: Maybe even
like at an earlier stage.

00:24:25.460 --> 00:24:28.280
So I think that in the
whole boredom of accounting,

00:24:28.280 --> 00:24:29.600
there is some--

00:24:29.600 --> 00:24:31.960
what I remember as
more interesting stuff.

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:35.840
It's like, everything that goes
on those statements you can--

00:24:35.840 --> 00:24:38.650
it's either market
value, cost value.

00:24:38.650 --> 00:24:41.440
So there's all sorts of--

00:24:41.440 --> 00:24:43.520
and you can get all
sorts of numbers

00:24:43.520 --> 00:24:47.190
depending on how
you value things.

00:24:47.190 --> 00:24:50.810
So my question would be
in those in these settings

00:24:50.810 --> 00:24:53.150
where I would
assume there's even

00:24:53.150 --> 00:24:56.720
measurement error in
prices and everything else,

00:24:56.720 --> 00:24:58.370
like how does that
all come together?

00:24:58.370 --> 00:25:00.578
And how do you think noise--

00:25:00.578 --> 00:25:02.370
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So
I'm going to take you--

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:03.110
yeah.

00:25:03.110 --> 00:25:05.360
So I'll take you through
a paper we wrote.

00:25:05.360 --> 00:25:08.780
I'm going to formalize the
notion of rate of return

00:25:08.780 --> 00:25:10.880
on assets, and
then I'll show you

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:14.720
one slide where we
did a lot of what--

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:17.550
the great virtue of
having all the data

00:25:17.550 --> 00:25:19.370
is we could do these
experiments, say, what

00:25:19.370 --> 00:25:22.460
if we didn't count something
we actually measured,

00:25:22.460 --> 00:25:24.497
or what if we know
change categories

00:25:24.497 --> 00:25:26.080
and put it in one
place and the other?

00:25:26.080 --> 00:25:29.270
So actually rank-ordered
the three things

00:25:29.270 --> 00:25:32.490
that matter most to
measuring productivity

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:36.170
so that we and especially
other researchers

00:25:36.170 --> 00:25:38.420
might be able to do better.

00:25:38.420 --> 00:25:40.840
Or not have to worry about
all the details on everything,

00:25:40.840 --> 00:25:41.990
that's more to the point.

00:25:41.990 --> 00:25:42.490
Yes?

00:25:42.490 --> 00:25:44.490
AUDIENCE: So what do you
do with households that

00:25:44.490 --> 00:25:45.750
also are running a business?

00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:48.866
Do you ask them only about
household inventories

00:25:48.866 --> 00:25:49.698
or the equivalent?

00:25:49.698 --> 00:25:51.740
ROBERT TOWNSEND: No, we
don't separate it at all.

00:25:51.740 --> 00:25:52.820
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:56.210
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So we treat
it as an integrated unit.

00:25:56.210 --> 00:26:01.520
And again, my view of it is,
households don't necessarily

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:02.860
make that separation.

00:26:02.860 --> 00:26:05.750
So we asked them
what is the profit

00:26:05.750 --> 00:26:07.250
from running the business?

00:26:07.250 --> 00:26:11.510
You're asking them
mentally to to separate out

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:14.480
all these things, to have
some money from wage earning

00:26:14.480 --> 00:26:15.720
and so on.

00:26:15.720 --> 00:26:20.150
So we prefer to
measure everything--

00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:21.020
AUDIENCE: Sorry.

00:26:21.020 --> 00:26:21.895
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yes?

00:26:21.895 --> 00:26:26.030
AUDIENCE: --quick follow-up
on [INAUDIBLE] question.

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:29.060
In this sense in
which households

00:26:29.060 --> 00:26:32.960
that are also a
business or just treated

00:26:32.960 --> 00:26:35.720
as a business and
consumption decisions

00:26:35.720 --> 00:26:37.850
are treated as a
unitary things--

00:26:37.850 --> 00:26:42.290
really this notion of some sort
of corporate thing going on,

00:26:42.290 --> 00:26:45.800
how do you then go into--

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:47.010
have you thought of--

00:26:47.010 --> 00:26:49.670
do you think it would be
interesting to like integrate

00:26:49.670 --> 00:26:54.710
that with household
decision-making modeling that

00:26:54.710 --> 00:26:57.570
also treats the household
as a corporate firm?

00:26:57.570 --> 00:27:01.670
So the idea of transaction
costs within the households,

00:27:01.670 --> 00:27:05.390
how like-- or the household then
is still a unitary thing which

00:27:05.390 --> 00:27:07.790
maybe doesn't make much sense
because there should be--

00:27:07.790 --> 00:27:10.953
there could be like the
woman is a manager of the--

00:27:10.953 --> 00:27:11.870
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:16.200
So there are two
things going on here.

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:19.880
One is household non-business
activities and the other

00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:23.180
is business activities,
and we prefer

00:27:23.180 --> 00:27:26.150
to try to measure all of that
and have an integrated account.

00:27:26.150 --> 00:27:28.600
Now in terms of--

00:27:28.600 --> 00:27:31.760
a household is collection
of individuals,

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:34.925
could we do the accounting
at the individual level?

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:40.040
In some instances,
we're painfully aware

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:44.150
that this notion we have
that this group of people

00:27:44.150 --> 00:27:47.960
is a household and is a
unit is stretching things,

00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:50.720
and yet that was our
starting point, to have

00:27:50.720 --> 00:27:52.910
a household-level survey.

00:27:52.910 --> 00:27:57.560
For one thing, the demands
even in the measurement

00:27:57.560 --> 00:28:02.060
of interviewing everybody
individually is horrendous.

00:28:02.060 --> 00:28:04.820
Also, you know some
assets are held jointly

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:08.180
or people may
disagree about who's

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:12.210
got the real claims on them.

00:28:12.210 --> 00:28:14.180
I mean, that said, there
are instances clearly

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:21.020
where the husband may be
hiding some of his income

00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:24.950
or the young teenager
still living at home

00:28:24.950 --> 00:28:28.670
actually have some earnings
in his or her bank account

00:28:28.670 --> 00:28:30.920
and that's kind of not
commingled with the rest

00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:36.290
of the family budget, and those
are real, real problems for us.

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:36.830
Yes?

00:28:36.830 --> 00:28:38.997
AUDIENCE: I mean, I think
to be fair to some extent,

00:28:38.997 --> 00:28:41.690
you can make that criticism of
corporate accounting as well,

00:28:41.690 --> 00:28:43.290
that maybe they're like--

00:28:43.290 --> 00:28:47.600
they're not acting as a unit or
there are people doing things

00:28:47.600 --> 00:28:49.245
that you can't see
in the accounts

00:28:49.245 --> 00:28:52.260
and that just looking
at a firm statement

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:54.260
would be different if you
would like to sit down

00:28:54.260 --> 00:28:55.850
with every member
of a corporate firm

00:28:55.850 --> 00:28:58.735
and ask, what did you
spend money on this month?

00:28:58.735 --> 00:29:00.360
Where did you-- all
this sort of stuff.

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:03.260
So I feel like to some
extent, the criticisms here

00:29:03.260 --> 00:29:06.260
are criticisms that apply to the
general framework of accounting

00:29:06.260 --> 00:29:08.860
and not to the household
problem specifically.

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:11.193
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah, there's
is some stuff I took out,

00:29:11.193 --> 00:29:13.730
otherwise the lecture
would be even longer, which

00:29:13.730 --> 00:29:18.380
is, do these problems-- you have
a conglomerate which consists

00:29:18.380 --> 00:29:22.360
of different firms, and
there are issues there

00:29:22.360 --> 00:29:26.260
about the flows from
one to the other.

00:29:26.260 --> 00:29:28.480
Here, you could treat a
marriage, for example,

00:29:28.480 --> 00:29:32.680
as a merger of two firms, and
there is development literature

00:29:32.680 --> 00:29:33.310
like that.

00:29:33.310 --> 00:29:35.950
Mark Rosenzweig
has written I think

00:29:35.950 --> 00:29:39.400
quite convincingly on
the marriage of daughters

00:29:39.400 --> 00:29:42.820
as basically insurance
and business transactions

00:29:42.820 --> 00:29:45.880
and so on.

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:53.120
So there are-- a divorce is
like a breakup and so on.

00:30:01.700 --> 00:30:05.240
We try to measure
liquidity, and so

00:30:05.240 --> 00:30:08.090
it's tempting to just
have everything in cash,

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:12.410
but actually here and in
India, grain, rice here,

00:30:12.410 --> 00:30:17.180
and sorghum in India is
people borrow and lend in it,

00:30:17.180 --> 00:30:18.890
they make commitments
to pay in it.

00:30:18.890 --> 00:30:23.630
So we actually have in
kind barter transactions.

00:30:23.630 --> 00:30:25.490
Now here again,
you could imagine--

00:30:25.490 --> 00:30:28.460
and when I teach
monetary economics,

00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:31.130
we get into this for sure.

00:30:31.130 --> 00:30:34.910
The notion of liquidity is how
quickly one could sell an asset

00:30:34.910 --> 00:30:37.520
or is there a deep
market for it.

00:30:37.520 --> 00:30:41.420
So this is, again, both
a judgment call here

00:30:41.420 --> 00:30:44.840
because we aggregate it
up, but also opens up

00:30:44.840 --> 00:30:49.460
a really interesting sort of
line of research where you

00:30:49.460 --> 00:30:53.360
can study liquidity and
transactions in these village

00:30:53.360 --> 00:30:55.550
economies.

00:30:55.550 --> 00:30:56.870
What to do with livestock?

00:30:59.630 --> 00:31:01.300
What does a cow--

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:07.460
a cash cow-- well, so we
just separate the asset

00:31:07.460 --> 00:31:09.560
from the income
and expense part.

00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:11.720
So the cow is the asset.

00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:16.170
The cow, if it's young, actually
appreciates in value over time.

00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:18.410
You get a capital
gain out of it.

00:31:18.410 --> 00:31:22.400
Cattle can die prematurely,
you'll get a capital loss.

00:31:22.400 --> 00:31:25.490
We actually try to
book all those things.

00:31:25.490 --> 00:31:28.940
Meanwhile, the cow-- the
dairy cattle up in Lopburi

00:31:28.940 --> 00:31:30.710
are delivering milk.

00:31:30.710 --> 00:31:33.590
So that's the revenue stream
off the asset, actually.

00:31:33.590 --> 00:31:36.990
It's a great analogy,
like fruit off the tree.

00:31:36.990 --> 00:31:40.030
They're not Lucas trees,
they're, I don't know,

00:31:40.030 --> 00:31:41.120
Lopburi animals.

00:31:45.220 --> 00:31:48.910
And gifts, as I've said--

00:31:48.910 --> 00:31:52.200
so I don't think
I'll belabor that.

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:55.020
I spared you a lot.

00:31:55.020 --> 00:31:57.450
Just want to
introduce the concept.

00:31:57.450 --> 00:32:00.240
In the underlying
data, you'll see

00:32:00.240 --> 00:32:05.140
a transaction, like received
wage income in cash.

00:32:05.140 --> 00:32:09.080
Now what to do with
the answer to that?

00:32:09.080 --> 00:32:10.530
50 baht.

00:32:10.530 --> 00:32:18.480
Well, it enters in all three
incomes, all three statements.

00:32:18.480 --> 00:32:23.070
Basically the cash enters an
increase in the balance sheet

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:25.020
as an increase in
a kind of asset,

00:32:25.020 --> 00:32:27.300
it's revenue on the
income statement,

00:32:27.300 --> 00:32:32.440
and it's incoming cash flow
on the statement of cash flow.

00:32:32.440 --> 00:32:35.160
Not every transaction
in the data

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:37.110
enter on all three accounts.

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:39.810
The struggle was
deciding indeed where

00:32:39.810 --> 00:32:43.620
to put all of these things,
although the accounting

00:32:43.620 --> 00:32:47.040
standards double-entry
bookkeeping does provide

00:32:47.040 --> 00:32:51.300
a discipline-- and yes,
we made mistakes initially

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:53.880
and things didn't add up.

00:32:53.880 --> 00:32:57.810
So then we realized we hadn't
entered things appropriately.

00:32:57.810 --> 00:33:00.210
That's what
double-entry bookkeeping

00:33:00.210 --> 00:33:02.580
is, some clerk having
all the transactions

00:33:02.580 --> 00:33:05.220
and then doing the books,
quote-unquote, consists

00:33:05.220 --> 00:33:09.300
of entering all those daily
transactions into ledgers

00:33:09.300 --> 00:33:13.670
and creating statements.

00:33:13.670 --> 00:33:16.460
So these happened to all be
cash transactions, that's

00:33:16.460 --> 00:33:19.070
kind of an accident,
it's just the first page

00:33:19.070 --> 00:33:21.930
of about eight or 10
of them in the book,

00:33:21.930 --> 00:33:25.080
and I'll skip the rest.

00:33:25.080 --> 00:33:28.560
Now let's talk about
liquidity management.

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:32.720
Here's a statement of
cash flow, D for deficit.

00:33:32.720 --> 00:33:34.100
So you run a deficit.

00:33:34.100 --> 00:33:37.310
The deficit, say, is the
difference between your income

00:33:37.310 --> 00:33:39.290
in a month--

00:33:39.290 --> 00:33:42.260
cash revenue, I should say--

00:33:42.260 --> 00:33:47.630
and, say, consumption--
minus consumption,

00:33:47.630 --> 00:33:49.700
minus investment, OK?

00:33:49.700 --> 00:33:54.410
So it's a deficit, you
had more demands for cash

00:33:54.410 --> 00:33:55.855
than you received in cash.

00:33:58.670 --> 00:34:04.870
Well, again, by the
construction of the accounts,

00:34:04.870 --> 00:34:06.460
everything has to balance.

00:34:06.460 --> 00:34:11.480
So we know exactly how
a deficit is financed.

00:34:11.480 --> 00:34:13.960
We even try to
measure the currency.

00:34:13.960 --> 00:34:18.070
So we have F1 through Fn
are these financing devices,

00:34:18.070 --> 00:34:20.650
and then you can
do a little math,

00:34:20.650 --> 00:34:24.969
basically, multiply
both sides by D,

00:34:24.969 --> 00:34:28.520
but D is the sum of the F,
so basically you get this,

00:34:28.520 --> 00:34:30.370
and then you square
it, and then you

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:33.820
divide by the different squared,
and all of a sudden you're

00:34:33.820 --> 00:34:36.040
looking at a variance--

00:34:36.040 --> 00:34:41.810
covariance decomposition,
which is exactly true.

00:34:41.810 --> 00:34:46.360
So if you want to know the role
that a particular financing

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:50.409
device like F1 is playing
in terms of smoothing

00:34:50.409 --> 00:34:54.790
the deficits, it's
basically like running

00:34:54.790 --> 00:35:02.440
a regression of the deficit
onto the financing device

00:35:02.440 --> 00:35:04.780
and getting a
regression coefficient.

00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:06.070
It's really cute.

00:35:06.070 --> 00:35:09.070
That you could do it
one financing device

00:35:09.070 --> 00:35:11.260
at a time and the sum
of those coefficients

00:35:11.260 --> 00:35:13.330
has to add up to 1.

00:35:13.330 --> 00:35:16.390
So this isn't the only
way to talk about--

00:35:19.010 --> 00:35:22.040
this is variance/covariance,
not order of magnitude.

00:35:22.040 --> 00:35:25.320
If you have two devices that
track each other perfectly

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:28.220
but there's always a
gap, this thing will say,

00:35:28.220 --> 00:35:31.790
it's the perfect smoother,
that's the thing that's used,

00:35:31.790 --> 00:35:33.380
but in fact, the gap remains.

00:35:33.380 --> 00:35:35.480
So you have to be a
little cautious about

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:37.100
the interpretation sometimes.

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:44.810
So how do you finance?

00:35:44.810 --> 00:35:47.380
Well you could
decrease your deposits

00:35:47.380 --> 00:35:52.990
if you have them in a financial
institution, you could--

00:35:52.990 --> 00:35:55.960
this is an odd way to put it--
decrease in your net ROSCA

00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:58.390
position, which means basically
you don't want to pay in,

00:35:58.390 --> 00:36:00.640
you want to get paid out.

00:36:00.640 --> 00:36:03.420
You want to be a recipient.

00:36:03.420 --> 00:36:07.240
You could call in your
loans, you could borrow,

00:36:07.240 --> 00:36:09.595
you could get gifts or
decrease your cash holdings.

00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:17.410
And for two case
study households,

00:36:17.410 --> 00:36:18.355
we actually measure--

00:36:21.450 --> 00:36:26.960
and you probably unfortunately
can't see it very well,

00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:33.430
but this cash is close to
100 or 1, basically, 100%.

00:36:36.100 --> 00:36:39.430
These numbers, though,
are the quartiles

00:36:39.430 --> 00:36:42.650
of the province in which this
case study household A lives.

00:36:42.650 --> 00:36:47.590
So the median is 76%, this
guy's actually on the high side,

00:36:47.590 --> 00:36:51.590
but still, in this
variance/covariance sense,

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:58.750
3/4 of the deficits is
households in Lopburi

00:36:58.750 --> 00:37:03.640
are financing their
deficits with cash.

00:37:03.640 --> 00:37:04.140
Cash.

00:37:04.140 --> 00:37:06.150
They're holding
great gobs of it.

00:37:06.150 --> 00:37:09.000
Unbelievable amounts
of it in the house.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:12.450
And when they get
these adverse shocks

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:16.683
or they have more expenses than
inputs, it outcomes to cash.

00:37:16.683 --> 00:37:18.850
You want to say, well why
isn't-- is it in a savings

00:37:18.850 --> 00:37:19.350
account?

00:37:19.350 --> 00:37:20.470
Not much.

00:37:20.470 --> 00:37:21.190
Negligible.

00:37:24.740 --> 00:37:28.800
Now I was a little
critical of this sort

00:37:28.800 --> 00:37:30.690
of measuring savings accounts.

00:37:30.690 --> 00:37:33.180
This is a measure
of savings account.

00:37:33.180 --> 00:37:35.340
I guess at the end
of the day, the issue

00:37:35.340 --> 00:37:38.430
is, are they managing
their cash well?

00:37:38.430 --> 00:37:39.792
This is the starting point.

00:37:39.792 --> 00:37:41.250
We have the
measurement, maybe they

00:37:41.250 --> 00:37:43.980
should be putting
more of it in the bank

00:37:43.980 --> 00:37:45.480
and taking it out
when they need it.

00:37:45.480 --> 00:37:51.450
They don't do it much, so
that is a bit of a puzzle.

00:37:51.450 --> 00:37:54.360
Gifts and loans are--

00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:55.620
I think this is not--

00:37:55.620 --> 00:37:58.922
this is out of the book
and not the latest version.

00:37:58.922 --> 00:38:00.130
AUDIENCE: This is the latest.

00:38:00.130 --> 00:38:02.340
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Is it?

00:38:02.340 --> 00:38:06.190
So OK.

00:38:06.190 --> 00:38:12.070
So you can see these upper
quartiles are getting up

00:38:12.070 --> 00:38:14.350
to 15%, 20%, 25%.

00:38:14.350 --> 00:38:21.220
So gifts are used
by some households

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:23.650
substantially as well.

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:26.647
It's not just a
pure cash economy.

00:38:29.815 --> 00:38:31.440
And like-- well that's
cash management.

00:38:31.440 --> 00:38:33.970
We can talk about
asset management.

00:38:33.970 --> 00:38:37.050
It's really the same
concept, except instead

00:38:37.050 --> 00:38:39.300
of operating on
the cash flow, you

00:38:39.300 --> 00:38:41.310
do this accrual notion
of accounting and look

00:38:41.310 --> 00:38:44.730
at sort of net savings.

00:38:44.730 --> 00:38:49.680
And I'll come back to
that later, essentially.

00:38:49.680 --> 00:38:51.570
And the portfolio management.

00:38:51.570 --> 00:38:55.010
So here, in answer
to the question that

00:38:55.010 --> 00:38:58.100
was raised earlier, is
looking at something

00:38:58.100 --> 00:39:02.690
like profits over assets,
which is a return on assets,

00:39:02.690 --> 00:39:09.830
and then creating 10
different measurements of it.

00:39:09.830 --> 00:39:13.340
Do you want to exclude household
consumption of their own output

00:39:13.340 --> 00:39:16.040
and not count it into income?

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:19.550
We counted total utility
expenses as a business expense,

00:39:19.550 --> 00:39:21.560
maybe we shouldn't
have done that.

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:24.680
Maybe it was a household
expense for, quote,

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:25.745
consumption purposes.

00:39:28.420 --> 00:39:30.730
So service flow
from fixed assets,

00:39:30.730 --> 00:39:33.290
which would be very natural
to do for durable goods,

00:39:33.290 --> 00:39:34.130
we tried that.

00:39:37.160 --> 00:39:40.047
We could take income but
then add gifts and transfers

00:39:40.047 --> 00:39:41.630
even though it's
really not associated

00:39:41.630 --> 00:39:44.960
with a project, and
especially this sort of cash.

00:39:47.630 --> 00:39:50.390
So it turned out
that this distinction

00:39:50.390 --> 00:39:54.890
of cash versus accrual
was very important.

00:39:54.890 --> 00:39:57.470
The treatment of gifts
was very important.

00:39:57.470 --> 00:40:00.260
And up here, which where I
didn't start, but I could,

00:40:00.260 --> 00:40:05.120
is in trying to get at the
cost of household labor--

00:40:05.120 --> 00:40:08.010
own household labor
used in production,

00:40:08.010 --> 00:40:13.460
that is a monster difficulty,
because you don't see for many

00:40:13.460 --> 00:40:17.510
of them what they would have
earned as wages in someone

00:40:17.510 --> 00:40:21.020
else's farm and so on, yet it's
clear that's very important

00:40:21.020 --> 00:40:22.891
and it makes a very
big difference.

00:40:26.120 --> 00:40:28.970
So hopefully knowing
that, one can bend over

00:40:28.970 --> 00:40:32.450
backwards to try to get a
better sense of the opportunity

00:40:32.450 --> 00:40:33.710
cost of labor.

00:40:33.710 --> 00:40:39.320
So as I said, let's look
at some uses of these.

00:40:39.320 --> 00:40:49.540
This is a paper with Anan
on the wealth distribution,

00:40:49.540 --> 00:40:53.340
and let's look at that 1%.

00:40:53.340 --> 00:40:54.330
Let's go get 'em.

00:40:54.330 --> 00:40:56.300
Let's get the top 1%.

00:40:56.300 --> 00:41:00.530
How much wealth does
the top 1% have?

00:41:00.530 --> 00:41:02.810
It's huge.

00:41:02.810 --> 00:41:08.540
They start out in 1999 with
about 35% of the total wealth.

00:41:11.530 --> 00:41:15.430
Now it's actually diminished.

00:41:15.430 --> 00:41:18.910
This is the-- frankly,
a wonderful thing

00:41:18.910 --> 00:41:21.190
to have all these many,
many years of data.

00:41:23.710 --> 00:41:26.110
It's diminished to 26%.

00:41:26.110 --> 00:41:29.400
What's going on is this
stuff at the bottom end

00:41:29.400 --> 00:41:35.770
where the bottom 50%
have 5% of the wealth.

00:41:35.770 --> 00:41:41.900
By the way, this is typical of
the US and European history,

00:41:41.900 --> 00:41:45.230
and it's very skewed
wealth distributions.

00:41:45.230 --> 00:41:49.790
But this thing actually
doubles over the space

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:53.110
of about 12 years here.

