So we can track
their net position

00:46:21.540 --> 00:46:24.930
in the distribution of
wealth, and here, you

00:46:24.930 --> 00:46:28.980
can see these
people climbing up,

00:46:28.980 --> 00:46:31.980
and other people,
quote, falling down.

00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:35.400
This is the histogram of
sort of in percentiles.

00:46:35.400 --> 00:46:40.460
By the way, the average
has to be 0 because it's--

00:46:40.460 --> 00:46:44.290
the net change is 0
over all the households,

00:46:44.290 --> 00:46:49.220
but you can see
some substantial--

00:46:49.220 --> 00:46:52.886
1 standard deviation is
like 14 percentage points.

00:46:52.886 --> 00:46:57.473
AUDIENCE: So do you have any
[INAUDIBLE] falling down?

00:46:57.473 --> 00:46:58.390
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

00:46:58.390 --> 00:47:02.990
So I guess one thing that sort
of got lost in the shuffle

00:47:02.990 --> 00:47:08.060
because we didn't decide
clearly whether it would show

00:47:08.060 --> 00:47:11.150
within the TA session or
I would show it here is

00:47:11.150 --> 00:47:13.400
kind of a life cycle picture.

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:19.090
So we've created
by cohorts, by age.

00:47:19.090 --> 00:47:23.250
And you can see, especially
in the areas near Bangkok,

00:47:23.250 --> 00:47:25.980
a classic life cycle.

00:47:25.980 --> 00:47:29.410
So as these
households are young,

00:47:29.410 --> 00:47:33.280
they start to accumulate
wealth, but after a while,

00:47:33.280 --> 00:47:34.990
especially as their
income falls off,

00:47:34.990 --> 00:47:36.680
they start running
down their assets.

00:47:36.680 --> 00:47:39.440
So this does not
distinguish by age.

00:47:39.440 --> 00:47:42.820
So it's a bit misleading,
it's not like there's some--

00:47:42.820 --> 00:47:46.240
necessarily some young household
that's just consistently eating

00:47:46.240 --> 00:47:49.090
more than their income.

00:47:49.090 --> 00:47:53.100
There are households like that,
and that raises this issue

00:47:53.100 --> 00:47:55.350
before of what's going on.

00:47:55.350 --> 00:47:59.910
I mean, if the husband
isn't there, for example,

00:47:59.910 --> 00:48:03.030
and the wife is running
some hair salon,

00:48:03.030 --> 00:48:07.110
she's consistently eating more
than then the household income,

00:48:07.110 --> 00:48:11.200
but you kind of wonder if
there isn't something going on,

00:48:11.200 --> 00:48:13.080
and we just don't
have the husband there

00:48:13.080 --> 00:48:17.430
who chooses either for
personal or occupation reasons

00:48:17.430 --> 00:48:20.790
to be in Bangkok the whole time.

00:48:20.790 --> 00:48:25.300
So then we get a
misleading picture

00:48:25.300 --> 00:48:34.020
that she may be in trouble or
she may know more the future

00:48:34.020 --> 00:48:34.620
than we do.

00:48:37.150 --> 00:48:41.750
So let's do a simple
decomposition.

00:48:41.750 --> 00:48:43.660
Here's savings.

00:48:43.660 --> 00:48:48.220
Savings on both sides
in absolute amount.

00:48:48.220 --> 00:48:50.860
And then divide and
multiply by profits

00:48:50.860 --> 00:48:53.470
from the household and
businesses, all of them

00:48:53.470 --> 00:48:57.040
summed up, and divide
and multiply by assets.

00:48:57.040 --> 00:48:59.200
So that has to be true.

00:48:59.200 --> 00:49:00.520
It's an identity.

00:49:00.520 --> 00:49:05.830
But savings over
basically profits

00:49:05.830 --> 00:49:10.810
is a savings rate out of
income, and profits over assets

00:49:10.810 --> 00:49:14.800
is the return on
assets post-multiplied

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:17.510
by the level of assets.

00:49:17.510 --> 00:49:22.600
So basically you can look at--

00:49:36.060 --> 00:49:41.010
you can look at the
change in wealth

00:49:41.010 --> 00:49:45.440
or the percentage change in
wealth, and wealth comes--

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:48.100
where is a change in
wealth coming from?

00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:52.170
It's coming from savings
plus income and gifts.

00:49:52.170 --> 00:49:55.450
The savings thing is
decomposed up here.

00:49:55.450 --> 00:49:59.370
So part of the mechanical
accounting drivers

00:49:59.370 --> 00:50:03.990
of increasing wealth has
to do with savings rates

00:50:03.990 --> 00:50:09.550
and rates of return on assets.

00:50:09.550 --> 00:50:12.080
And maybe gifts if
they're important.

00:50:12.080 --> 00:50:16.630
So here is the
correlation of the growth

00:50:16.630 --> 00:50:21.903
of net worth with savings
rates, and depending

00:50:21.903 --> 00:50:23.320
on whether the
unit of observation

00:50:23.320 --> 00:50:26.770
is household month or household
year or households averaged up

00:50:26.770 --> 00:50:30.010
over all of the months
and years of the data,

00:50:30.010 --> 00:50:36.940
you do see some positive
significant correlations.

00:50:36.940 --> 00:50:40.390
So in fact, not
too surprisingly,

00:50:40.390 --> 00:50:43.450
some of the increase
in net worth

00:50:43.450 --> 00:50:48.580
is coming from households
who have high savings rates.

00:50:48.580 --> 00:50:54.740
But the bigger part of the
story is the correlation

00:50:54.740 --> 00:50:57.620
with the return on assets.

00:50:57.620 --> 00:51:02.420
And there, it's consistent
pretty much at all levels.

00:51:06.190 --> 00:51:10.030
So household by household
with our measurement,

00:51:10.030 --> 00:51:13.930
we look at their productivity
in terms of rate of return,

00:51:13.930 --> 00:51:17.720
and then see whether their net
wealth is going up or down,

00:51:17.720 --> 00:51:20.650
and it's the households who
have high rates of return who

00:51:20.650 --> 00:51:22.420
have the high--

00:51:22.420 --> 00:51:24.810
highest rates of increase
in their net worth.

00:51:30.040 --> 00:51:31.620
And it's quite persistent.

00:51:31.620 --> 00:51:35.820
Here, we look at return on
assets in the first half

00:51:35.820 --> 00:51:40.830
and second half of the sample
at the time that we did it.

00:51:40.830 --> 00:51:46.350
So if they were identical, they
would lie on a 45-degree line,

00:51:46.350 --> 00:51:50.670
and these scatter points are
close with one exception, which

00:51:50.670 --> 00:51:53.802
is Buriram.

00:51:53.802 --> 00:51:55.930
Oh, you should be thinking
models at this point.

00:51:55.930 --> 00:52:01.110
Remember the productivity,
the TFP thing?

00:52:01.110 --> 00:52:03.975
That's the thing sitting outside
multiplicatively in front

00:52:03.975 --> 00:52:05.100
of the production function?

00:52:05.100 --> 00:52:08.730
These are household-specific
TFP numbers sort of.

00:52:08.730 --> 00:52:11.280
It's not a very sophisticated--
production function

00:52:11.280 --> 00:52:12.930
is just linear.

00:52:12.930 --> 00:52:15.890
So it's not really just--

00:52:15.890 --> 00:52:19.080
you'd rather have like the
marginal product of capital

00:52:19.080 --> 00:52:23.160
and pre-multiply, this is a
linear production function.

00:52:23.160 --> 00:52:27.770
The marginal product
is just the average.

00:52:27.770 --> 00:52:28.840
But it's very persistent.

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:34.300
So in these models, the issue
is, are those TFP shocks IID

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:36.070
over households,
are they the same

00:52:36.070 --> 00:52:38.190
unless you get blasted
with some shock?

00:52:38.190 --> 00:52:42.010
And this suggests that
the household level

00:52:42.010 --> 00:52:43.950
it's really quite persistent.

00:52:43.950 --> 00:52:50.690
Buriram is an
interesting exception,

00:52:50.690 --> 00:52:52.760
and I'll just say
it in words, there

00:52:52.760 --> 00:52:57.020
are many more occupations
shifts in Buriram

00:52:57.020 --> 00:52:59.390
than in the other
three provinces.

00:52:59.390 --> 00:53:03.870
It turns out these villages
aren't really villages anymore,

00:53:03.870 --> 00:53:06.350
they've paved over our
soil moisture readers

00:53:06.350 --> 00:53:09.350
and they become
part of the town.

00:53:09.350 --> 00:53:11.720
There's a big construction
boom going on.

00:53:11.720 --> 00:53:14.540
Part of that is
pararubber, part of it

00:53:14.540 --> 00:53:19.580
is Scandinavian tourists
coming in marrying Thai women

00:53:19.580 --> 00:53:23.282
and staying.

00:53:23.282 --> 00:53:26.990
The place is just like
a construction boom.

00:53:26.990 --> 00:53:30.320
So people shifted
from rice-growing

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:32.780
or money-lending or
other things to laying

00:53:32.780 --> 00:53:35.420
tile and all these
things, and they

00:53:35.420 --> 00:53:37.310
had a higher return
on their assets

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:40.700
as a result on average
of those switches.

00:53:40.700 --> 00:53:42.120
So that's kind of reassuring.

00:53:42.120 --> 00:53:44.360
It's another sense
in which households

00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:47.960
are aware of their success.

00:53:47.960 --> 00:53:51.560
And here, coming back
to Witt's question,

00:53:51.560 --> 00:53:54.600
if you partition
into low, medium,

00:53:54.600 --> 00:53:56.510
and high return on
assets and looked

00:53:56.510 --> 00:54:01.850
at what they did with
their increasing wealth,

00:54:01.850 --> 00:54:08.050
these high ROA guys are putting
money back in the business.

00:54:08.050 --> 00:54:10.460
They're buying equipment,
they're investing and putting

00:54:10.460 --> 00:54:12.940
it into their business.

00:54:12.940 --> 00:54:16.100
And that's not true of
the medium or low guys.

00:54:16.100 --> 00:54:18.120
These guys are doing
the financial assets.

00:54:18.120 --> 00:54:21.680
So more of their
increasing financial wealth

00:54:21.680 --> 00:54:27.440
is potentially in cash, but to
the extent that we measured ROA

00:54:27.440 --> 00:54:29.390
accurately, which
we have tried very

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:32.120
hard to do in all kinds of
different ways, we're getting

00:54:32.120 --> 00:54:35.240
the reinforcing message
here that we've measured it

00:54:35.240 --> 00:54:38.775
accurately because they seem
to do what you would think,

00:54:38.775 --> 00:54:41.150
which is, you're not going to
put your money in a savings

00:54:41.150 --> 00:54:45.150
account when you've got
a really high return.

00:54:45.150 --> 00:54:47.910
And later in another lecture
will try to adjust for risk.

00:54:51.340 --> 00:54:57.380
So now we'll aggregate
it up to villages

00:54:57.380 --> 00:54:59.090
and use those same
financial accounts.

00:55:03.120 --> 00:55:06.260
We do have to struggle
again with this dual role

00:55:06.260 --> 00:55:11.210
that households play as
consumers and producers.

00:55:11.210 --> 00:55:14.140
So much of economics
is driven by here

00:55:14.140 --> 00:55:17.690
is firms maximizing profits,
here is households maximizing

00:55:17.690 --> 00:55:19.820
utility-- these are
households running businesses,

00:55:19.820 --> 00:55:21.660
so what are we going to do?

00:55:21.660 --> 00:55:25.590
And in particular, what are
we going to do with the labor?

00:55:25.590 --> 00:55:28.910
Well, we made a decision,
although here, we do

00:55:28.910 --> 00:55:31.180
check and do robustness checks.

00:55:31.180 --> 00:55:33.320
And what I'm going
to show you today

00:55:33.320 --> 00:55:36.500
is treating even the
labor income as something

00:55:36.500 --> 00:55:42.620
like consulting income, like
they're providing a service--

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:45.110
their business is
to provide a labor

00:55:45.110 --> 00:55:48.440
service to other households,
and they get profits from that.

00:55:54.820 --> 00:55:58.420
Now if you think about a
production sector and aggregate

00:55:58.420 --> 00:56:03.850
up, to the extent that inputs
from one business are--

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:06.310
the outputs from one business
are an input to the other,

00:56:06.310 --> 00:56:08.620
the net is zero and
it doesn't count.

00:56:08.620 --> 00:56:12.220
But in these villages,
the output of one business

00:56:12.220 --> 00:56:15.760
could be someone
else's consumption,

00:56:15.760 --> 00:56:18.200
and it doesn't net out.

00:56:18.200 --> 00:56:20.030
Both get measured.

00:56:20.030 --> 00:56:22.580
As it would if you're
distinguishing households

00:56:22.580 --> 00:56:25.190
from firms.

00:56:25.190 --> 00:56:28.940
We can actually measure and
ask about the transactions.

00:56:28.940 --> 00:56:32.750
So we know the transaction
partners almost.

00:56:32.750 --> 00:56:36.050
We did screw up with
consumption because we

00:56:36.050 --> 00:56:38.150
forgot to ask
consistently where they

00:56:38.150 --> 00:56:42.230
buy stuff, which has to do with
the price thing also mentioned

00:56:42.230 --> 00:56:43.730
earlier.

00:56:43.730 --> 00:56:45.680
But fortunately,
and I'm sure you'll

00:56:45.680 --> 00:56:48.260
be more than happy to
take my word for it,

00:56:48.260 --> 00:56:52.550
there is an accounting identity,
so you can kind of back up

00:56:52.550 --> 00:56:57.770
as a residual how much of
that output is basically

00:56:57.770 --> 00:57:01.850
sold and consumed in the village
because we measured everything

00:57:01.850 --> 00:57:03.300
else.

00:57:03.300 --> 00:57:05.197
In other words, on
the buying side,

00:57:05.197 --> 00:57:07.780
we don't see it, but-- because
we don't know where they bought

00:57:07.780 --> 00:57:10.210
it, but we actually figured
out on the selling side

00:57:10.210 --> 00:57:12.965
that it came from somebody who
produced it in the village.

00:57:20.060 --> 00:57:21.740
Measurement error,
you asked-- somebody

00:57:21.740 --> 00:57:25.070
asked about the rich
guys not participating.

00:57:25.070 --> 00:57:28.730
If a moneylender were
like the central node

00:57:28.730 --> 00:57:32.690
and the money lender refused
to answer our questions,

00:57:32.690 --> 00:57:34.190
we're going to get
really screwed up

00:57:34.190 --> 00:57:38.127
in terms of the flow of funds
and the balance of payments

00:57:38.127 --> 00:57:38.960
and everything else.

00:57:38.960 --> 00:57:41.600
Because we are going to act
like the average overall--

00:57:41.600 --> 00:57:45.260
the households in the
village is the representation

00:57:45.260 --> 00:57:49.397
of what's going on in the
village itself as a whole.

00:57:49.397 --> 00:57:51.230
To the extent that
there's measurement error

00:57:51.230 --> 00:57:53.935
but there is IID
over households,

00:57:53.935 --> 00:57:56.060
and to the extent that we
have a lot of households,

00:57:56.060 --> 00:57:59.120
then hopefully that
helps make the case

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:02.750
that we've got a
reasonably good measure.

00:58:10.690 --> 00:58:14.225
So how do you create
these accounts?

00:58:17.550 --> 00:58:20.035
What is GNP anyway?

00:58:20.035 --> 00:58:20.535
GDP?

00:58:23.130 --> 00:58:26.674
Everyone seems to be
obsessed about it.

00:58:26.674 --> 00:58:31.180
OK, it just comes from
the income statement.

00:58:31.180 --> 00:58:33.660
So basically, here's
a statement of income,

00:58:33.660 --> 00:58:35.340
it's what you would expect.

00:58:35.340 --> 00:58:39.000
You've got revenues come from
production, or for that matter,

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:42.390
if you're a lender or
saver from interest,

00:58:42.390 --> 00:58:43.620
you've got capital gains.

00:58:43.620 --> 00:58:46.230
You subtract off
capital losses, maybe

00:58:46.230 --> 00:58:51.870
you have sort of a paid payment
from an insurance indemnity.

00:58:51.870 --> 00:58:54.900
So those are revenues,
here is basically expenses,

00:58:54.900 --> 00:58:56.940
production expenses,
interest expenses

00:58:56.940 --> 00:59:01.910
on loans, depreciation,
insurance premia, taxes, et

00:59:01.910 --> 00:59:02.440
cetera.

00:59:02.440 --> 00:59:10.960
So net income before tax--

00:59:10.960 --> 00:59:13.920
before income tax but
after property tax

00:59:13.920 --> 00:59:16.350
is what makes these things
balance because this

00:59:16.350 --> 00:59:17.610
is basically the profit--

00:59:17.610 --> 00:59:21.920
it's basically
revenues less expenses.

00:59:21.920 --> 00:59:26.060
So that should be
comfortable, sound sort of

00:59:26.060 --> 00:59:28.310
reassuringly familiar.

00:59:28.310 --> 00:59:33.740
All that we do is
basically take this stuff

00:59:33.740 --> 00:59:36.440
and subtract it off
from both sides.

00:59:36.440 --> 00:59:38.420
That cancels it out
on the right-hand side

00:59:38.420 --> 00:59:41.160
and puts it on the
left-hand side.

00:59:41.160 --> 00:59:46.970
So basically you have production
revenue less production

00:59:46.970 --> 00:59:59.070
expenses, and that's
basically the rest

00:59:59.070 --> 01:00:02.470
is equal to the payments
to factors of production.

01:00:02.470 --> 01:00:05.220
So you're paying
stuff out in interest,

01:00:05.220 --> 01:00:11.230
you're paying out in taxes,
depreciation is over here,

01:00:11.230 --> 01:00:14.940
and you're paying out to
the owners of the enterprise

01:00:14.940 --> 01:00:17.250
namely profits.

01:00:17.250 --> 01:00:20.430
So you may remember
vaguely that there's

01:00:20.430 --> 01:00:24.810
two ways to measure
income on the output side

01:00:24.810 --> 01:00:28.140
and on the factor payment side,
and they add up to each other.

01:00:28.140 --> 01:00:33.240
So this is
value-added, basically.

01:00:33.240 --> 01:00:37.170
The only catch here is
the way we treated labor,

01:00:37.170 --> 01:00:40.080
you don't see a labor
expense over here,

01:00:40.080 --> 01:00:42.330
because normally
value-added, you're

01:00:42.330 --> 01:00:45.810
only subtracting off
intermediate inputs

01:00:45.810 --> 01:00:48.720
and other purchased inputs,
but here, we actually subtract

01:00:48.720 --> 01:00:53.820
off the labor because of
the way we conceptualize

01:00:53.820 --> 01:00:59.200
that problem or that issue.

01:00:59.200 --> 01:01:03.150
So you want to see what's
happening over time in the four

01:01:03.150 --> 01:01:09.400
provinces, four villages
per province, Chachoengsao

01:01:09.400 --> 01:01:17.080
GDP or really village product is
going down pretty consistently.

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:20.080
Now what happened is the
shrimp ponds, basically,

01:01:20.080 --> 01:01:21.970
people had
converted-- yeah, that

01:01:21.970 --> 01:01:24.160
stuff you're buying
in Costco or Walmart,

01:01:24.160 --> 01:01:25.660
those are typically Thai shrimp.

01:01:28.840 --> 01:01:33.390
But the ponds-- so
there's some disease.

01:01:33.390 --> 01:01:38.010
And so-- and household,
some of them switched.

01:01:38.010 --> 01:01:41.180
And the fish and others
now are actually,

01:01:41.180 --> 01:01:43.670
with the world grain prices
being relatively high,

01:01:43.670 --> 01:01:49.027
they're refilling in the
ponds and planting rice again.

01:01:49.027 --> 01:01:49.610
AUDIENCE: Rob?

01:01:49.610 --> 01:01:50.050
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yes?

01:01:50.050 --> 01:01:52.370
AUDIENCE: What are the different
colored lines [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:52.370 --> 01:01:53.580
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Each
of four villages.

01:01:53.580 --> 01:01:53.930
So--

01:01:53.930 --> 01:01:54.763
AUDIENCE: Oh, I see.

01:01:54.763 --> 01:01:56.740
[INAUDIBLE]

01:01:56.740 --> 01:01:59.560
ROBERT TOWNSEND: So you
can see, is every village

01:01:59.560 --> 01:02:00.640
like every other village?

01:02:00.640 --> 01:02:03.550
Well, to some degree, yes,
but the levels are different,

01:02:03.550 --> 01:02:09.460
and sometimes even the movements
over time are a bit different.

01:02:09.460 --> 01:02:11.620
Another thing to watch
out for is the scale here,

01:02:11.620 --> 01:02:16.450
because in order to clearly
display each village--

01:02:16.450 --> 01:02:18.910
each of the four villages in
a province, where changing

01:02:18.910 --> 01:02:20.570
the scale of a province.

01:02:20.570 --> 01:02:23.920
Sisaket is a lot poorer than--

01:02:23.920 --> 01:02:27.760
even in their worst days,
Chachoengsao villages

01:02:27.760 --> 01:02:38.060
are better off
substantially than Sisaket.

01:02:38.060 --> 01:02:42.500
So the income levels
are maybe on average

01:02:42.500 --> 01:02:44.400
three times higher
in Chachoengsao.

01:02:48.130 --> 01:02:52.200
They're almost ordered by
their distance to Bangkok.

01:02:52.200 --> 01:02:54.440
I won't bore you with this.

01:02:54.440 --> 01:02:56.130
This is just to
what do households

01:02:56.130 --> 01:02:59.375
do with their profits?

01:02:59.375 --> 01:03:04.410
And then the story is mostly
in the northeast. they eat it.

01:03:04.410 --> 01:03:08.010
And in central region, they're
more likely to put it back

01:03:08.010 --> 01:03:12.750
in the business or their
farm as retained earnings.

01:03:12.750 --> 01:03:19.250
Savings investment
account, that's

01:03:19.250 --> 01:03:21.540
probably worth looking at.

01:03:21.540 --> 01:03:23.010
Here's the balance sheet.

01:03:23.010 --> 01:03:26.940
So remember, we had assets
and liabilities and net worth.

01:03:26.940 --> 01:03:31.190
This is the change over
time in the balance sheet.

01:03:31.190 --> 01:03:34.710
So it's like a
first-time difference.

01:03:34.710 --> 01:03:40.960
So changes in liabilities
and changes in net worth

01:03:40.960 --> 01:03:46.060
must equal to the change
in all the assets,

01:03:46.060 --> 01:03:48.880
especially if you include
change in net worth over there.

01:03:51.630 --> 01:03:55.270
These could be
financial or real.

01:03:55.270 --> 01:03:58.770
Well hopefully this is
comfortable and familiar.

01:03:58.770 --> 01:04:01.830
Just the notion of having assets
and liabilities and net worth

01:04:01.830 --> 01:04:04.170
and taking a time difference.

01:04:04.170 --> 01:04:07.310
What is the savings
investment account?

01:04:07.310 --> 01:04:10.970
Well, you just basically take
the change in liabilities

01:04:10.970 --> 01:04:14.420
and put it on the
left-hand side.

01:04:14.420 --> 01:04:18.870
That leaves the change in net
worth on the right-hand side,

01:04:18.870 --> 01:04:21.800
and then what you do with
it on the left-hand side.

01:04:21.800 --> 01:04:22.580
Yes?

01:04:22.580 --> 01:04:26.660
AUDIENCE: So before we were
talking about household gifts

01:04:26.660 --> 01:04:28.395
equity.

01:04:28.395 --> 01:04:29.270
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yep.

01:04:29.270 --> 01:04:30.978
AUDIENCE: So does that
mean that they get

01:04:30.978 --> 01:04:32.380
counted as financial assets?

01:04:36.270 --> 01:04:38.613
Where would gifts
in a village enter?

01:04:38.613 --> 01:04:40.155
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
Contributed capital.

01:04:40.155 --> 01:04:41.270
AUDIENCE: Contributed capital.

01:04:41.270 --> 01:04:41.720
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

01:04:41.720 --> 01:04:43.127
That's what we called it.

01:04:43.127 --> 01:04:43.544
AUDIENCE: All right.

01:04:43.544 --> 01:04:43.961
Cool.

01:04:43.961 --> 01:04:44.380
Thanks.

01:04:44.380 --> 01:04:45.140
I'm sorry, it just occurred to--

01:04:45.140 --> 01:04:45.980
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
No, no, it's fine.

01:04:45.980 --> 01:04:47.070
AUDIENCE: --no idea
where they're going.

01:04:47.070 --> 01:04:48.237
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah, yeah.

01:04:48.237 --> 01:04:51.018
It's there, because if
they're getting gifts and not

01:04:51.018 --> 01:04:53.060
eating too much, it should
increase their wealth,

01:04:53.060 --> 01:04:55.640
and therefore, it should show
up somewhere as either reduced

01:04:55.640 --> 01:04:58.640
debt or increased assets.

01:04:58.640 --> 01:05:04.850
And that phenomenon depends
a lot on where you are.

01:05:04.850 --> 01:05:07.210
AUDIENCE: But entered
both sides, right?

01:05:07.210 --> 01:05:10.762
It entered as increased cash,
and then also increased--

01:05:10.762 --> 01:05:11.720
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Well--

01:05:11.720 --> 01:05:12.560
AUDIENCE: --contributed capital.

01:05:12.560 --> 01:05:14.102
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
The concept is here.

01:05:14.102 --> 01:05:16.610
So basically say
this is positive,

01:05:16.610 --> 01:05:20.550
and your change in
net worth is positive

01:05:20.550 --> 01:05:23.760
because either retained
earnings or contributed capital.

01:05:23.760 --> 01:05:25.920
And then the issue is
portfolio management,

01:05:25.920 --> 01:05:27.900
it's what did you do with it?

01:05:27.900 --> 01:05:32.260
And you could put it in cash,
that's in financial assets,

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:38.580
but you could also have it in
inventory as I was alluding to,

01:05:38.580 --> 01:05:43.990
or have livestock assets
or other fixed assets.

01:05:43.990 --> 01:05:46.180
So it's worthy of
study to figure out

01:05:46.180 --> 01:05:48.268
what they're doing with it.

01:05:48.268 --> 01:05:49.726
AUDIENCE: And
sometimes the idea is

01:05:49.726 --> 01:05:51.730
there's a reciprocity,
and the gift that I

01:05:51.730 --> 01:05:55.690
give to my buddy in
the next village is

01:05:55.690 --> 01:05:56.840
in some sense a residual--

01:05:56.840 --> 01:05:57.757
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

01:05:57.757 --> 01:05:58.690
AUDIENCE: So yeah.

01:05:58.690 --> 01:05:58.930
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

01:05:58.930 --> 01:06:00.290
AUDIENCE: So yea, I
guess that's what--

01:06:00.290 --> 01:06:01.690
ROBERT TOWNSEND: I mean,
the extreme versions of that

01:06:01.690 --> 01:06:04.030
would be the kids
that go off to Bangkok

01:06:04.030 --> 01:06:06.150
and they send money back.

01:06:06.150 --> 01:06:08.110
Now can you distinguish
they're just

01:06:08.110 --> 01:06:09.640
caring about their parents?

01:06:09.640 --> 01:06:14.500
And there's a very strong
Thai tradition there.

01:06:14.500 --> 01:06:18.010
But then eventually they
come back and run the farm.

01:06:24.590 --> 01:06:27.080
But it is-- it's a
real incoming flow,

01:06:27.080 --> 01:06:29.060
so we have to do
something with it.

01:06:29.060 --> 01:06:32.297
We could just not call
it equity or something,

01:06:32.297 --> 01:06:34.130
and in effect, that's
what we're doing here,

01:06:34.130 --> 01:06:39.510
is just keeping track of it
separately as a line item.

01:06:39.510 --> 01:06:40.010
OK.

01:06:40.010 --> 01:06:47.300
So I guess I said this before.

01:06:47.300 --> 01:06:50.480
Oh, by the way, on the
lifecycle diagrams,

01:06:50.480 --> 01:06:56.350
it's really dramatic
that in the northeast,

01:06:56.350 --> 01:06:59.890
wealth isn't dropping
as these guys get older,

01:06:59.890 --> 01:07:01.780
and likewise, they're
not accumulating

01:07:01.780 --> 01:07:05.800
a lot of financial or real
assets as they're young

01:07:05.800 --> 01:07:07.540
and getting older either.

01:07:07.540 --> 01:07:09.970
There doesn't seem to
be this life cycle,

01:07:09.970 --> 01:07:12.470
and the gifts just
get bigger and bigger.

01:07:12.470 --> 01:07:15.910
You don't have to get
older to get those gifts.

01:07:15.910 --> 01:07:16.840
It's the huge--

01:07:16.840 --> 01:07:21.940
I think it's overlapping
generations, essentially.

01:07:21.940 --> 01:07:25.440
It's really quite different
between the northeast

01:07:25.440 --> 01:07:28.000
and the central area,
and that's related,

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:30.585
because it's kind
of showing up here.

01:07:30.585 --> 01:07:32.335
So then we get to the
balance of payments.

01:07:39.830 --> 01:07:44.420
So basically, villages trade.

01:07:44.420 --> 01:07:47.480
They produce stuff and
sell it and they buy stuff

01:07:47.480 --> 01:07:50.040
as inputs and by consumption.

01:07:50.040 --> 01:07:54.260
So we got sort of a trade
balance that we measure.

01:07:54.260 --> 01:07:59.180
You could add in interest
earnings from, quote, abroad,

01:07:59.180 --> 01:08:01.520
but it's really mostly
from the same country.

01:08:01.520 --> 01:08:03.440
They're getting interest
on savings accounts

01:08:03.440 --> 01:08:07.410
that they held outside the
village or in those gifts

01:08:07.410 --> 01:08:07.910
again.

01:08:11.470 --> 01:08:14.740
So you may or may
not have seen this,

01:08:14.740 --> 01:08:17.080
this gets really
kind of confusing

01:08:17.080 --> 01:08:20.140
the way the standard
accounting is done.

01:08:20.140 --> 01:08:26.410
Trade balance plus this other
earnings on gifts and interest

01:08:26.410 --> 01:08:28.870
is called the current
account, and then you

01:08:28.870 --> 01:08:31.990
have the current
account balanced

01:08:31.990 --> 01:08:35.109
with the financial count
and the capital account.

01:08:35.109 --> 01:08:36.970
But they didn't
write current account

01:08:36.970 --> 01:08:42.490
equal financial account,
so this stuff has

01:08:42.490 --> 01:08:48.609
to be-- if you're trading
a lot, like China,

01:08:48.609 --> 01:08:51.640
and you have a big sort
of current account,

01:08:51.640 --> 01:08:54.569
this stuff has to be negative.

01:08:54.569 --> 01:08:56.660
A negative in the
financial account

01:08:56.660 --> 01:08:58.710
is actually, quote, a
good thing in the sense

01:08:58.710 --> 01:09:03.050
that you're accumulating assets.

01:09:03.050 --> 01:09:06.270
But believe me, it'll
throw you every time when

01:09:06.270 --> 01:09:09.330
you start thinking about it.

01:09:09.330 --> 01:09:12.210
And then I won't
drive this for you,

01:09:12.210 --> 01:09:14.700
but it turns out that
if you take this sort

01:09:14.700 --> 01:09:19.109
of Keynesian-looking
thing, which is really just

01:09:19.109 --> 01:09:23.340
an accounting statement,
income less consumption less

01:09:23.340 --> 01:09:27.029
investment plus transfers--
that's not taxes--

01:09:27.029 --> 01:09:32.340
has to be identically
equal to the trade balance

01:09:32.340 --> 01:09:35.220
plus sort of capital
account balance, which

01:09:35.220 --> 01:09:39.069
we keep track of separately,
plus the change in inventories.

01:09:39.069 --> 01:09:44.430
So largely, if they
run an export surplus,

01:09:44.430 --> 01:09:47.064
they're going to save
it, but not quite.

01:09:47.064 --> 01:09:48.689
Because they have
other ways of saving,

01:09:48.689 --> 01:09:51.569
you have to adjust for
changes in the capital,

01:09:51.569 --> 01:09:54.990
buying and selling with
foreigners, so to speak,

01:09:54.990 --> 01:09:56.490
and the changes in inventory.

01:09:56.490 --> 01:09:59.424
AUDIENCE: So the left-hand
side is a financial account

01:09:59.424 --> 01:10:01.325
in this case?

01:10:01.325 --> 01:10:02.700
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
It's not obvious

01:10:02.700 --> 01:10:05.750
how you get from this to this.

01:10:05.750 --> 01:10:10.250
And I decided not to
try to derive it today.

01:10:10.250 --> 01:10:12.050
But it is an identity.

01:10:12.050 --> 01:10:13.370
One follows from the other.

01:10:17.520 --> 01:10:18.970
And here, the
balance of payments

01:10:18.970 --> 01:10:24.220
accounts for these
villages, mostly

01:10:24.220 --> 01:10:27.440
this story is they're
running surpluses.

01:10:27.440 --> 01:10:31.410
The trade or trade and
current account is this blue

01:10:31.410 --> 01:10:34.860
or blue-red stuff, and--

01:10:34.860 --> 01:10:36.720
although here you
see a difference.

01:10:36.720 --> 01:10:39.680
Chachoengsao's
getting in trouble,

01:10:39.680 --> 01:10:43.530
its balance of payments
is going down in the sense

01:10:43.530 --> 01:10:47.640
that it's running less
and less of a surplus.

01:10:47.640 --> 01:10:50.140
Whereas Lopburi is
the other story.

01:10:50.140 --> 01:10:51.480
It's always increasing.

01:10:51.480 --> 01:10:54.330
The difference
between red and blue

01:10:54.330 --> 01:10:59.700
is basically the gifts that play
a big role in the northeast.

01:10:59.700 --> 01:11:03.180
And here's an instance
of Buriram coming off

01:11:03.180 --> 01:11:08.040
the financial crisis,
which was 1997-98,

01:11:08.040 --> 01:11:11.640
but anyway, they actually ran
a balance of payments deficit.

01:11:16.280 --> 01:11:20.860
So this opens up the whole
vista of international economics

01:11:20.860 --> 01:11:23.200
and what's going on
using those kinds of ways

01:11:23.200 --> 01:11:25.660
of conceptualizing the problem.

01:11:29.030 --> 01:11:33.980
And just to remind you, because
I promised an application

01:11:33.980 --> 01:11:37.520
for each section, we've
had tons of models

01:11:37.520 --> 01:11:43.160
of the role of financing
constraints or other obstacles

01:11:43.160 --> 01:11:46.980
in growth and TFP and
so on and so forth.

01:11:46.980 --> 01:11:56.310
So here's just some model with
arch where we do the following.

01:11:56.310 --> 01:12:00.070
We take these villages to
be small open economies,

01:12:00.070 --> 01:12:03.010
we see a drop in
the interest rate--

01:12:03.010 --> 01:12:06.470
it's actually true worldwide--

01:12:06.470 --> 01:12:10.940
and we see the
number of new loans

01:12:10.940 --> 01:12:15.590
increasing this has to do in
part with this village fund

01:12:15.590 --> 01:12:19.430
stuff that we'll talk about
later the Million Baht

01:12:19.430 --> 01:12:20.240
Fund in Thailand.

01:12:23.050 --> 01:12:26.750
This is the collateral
constraint--

01:12:26.750 --> 01:12:29.500
this is a model thing.

01:12:29.500 --> 01:12:34.110
So we're going to act as if that
innovation associated with more

01:12:34.110 --> 01:12:37.590
loans was like a weakening
of the borrowing constraint

01:12:37.590 --> 01:12:46.270
and feed it into
a model, and it's

01:12:46.270 --> 01:12:51.680
a trade model with
financial underpinnings,

01:12:51.680 --> 01:12:55.940
and it predicts things like the
relative price of agriculture

01:12:55.940 --> 01:12:59.340
relative to manufactured goods.

01:12:59.340 --> 01:13:03.240
In the model and in the
data, we're kind of close.

01:13:03.240 --> 01:13:09.120
And a real goal was to try
to get the wages right,

01:13:09.120 --> 01:13:13.785
and here is the actual and
model-driven real wages.

01:13:16.540 --> 01:13:17.870
Why is this a struggle?

01:13:17.870 --> 01:13:21.030
If you think about
Heckscher-Ohlin,

01:13:21.030 --> 01:13:24.600
that has to do with
the area around Bangkok

01:13:24.600 --> 01:13:29.070
being very capital-intensive
and not having so much labor,

01:13:29.070 --> 01:13:33.120
so interest rates are
lower and wages are higher;

01:13:33.120 --> 01:13:36.290
in the northeast, it's the
other way around because capital

01:13:36.290 --> 01:13:38.500
and wealth is relatively low.

01:13:38.500 --> 01:13:40.110
So you think that
over time you're

01:13:40.110 --> 01:13:42.750
going to get
convergence, which means

01:13:42.750 --> 01:13:46.710
wages ought to be dropping
in the central area,

01:13:46.710 --> 01:13:49.120
and they're not.

01:13:49.120 --> 01:13:53.070
So then you introduce
this financial constraint,

01:13:53.070 --> 01:13:55.350
and you get the
dynamics that have

01:13:55.350 --> 01:13:57.550
to do with choosing
occupations and so on.

01:13:57.550 --> 01:14:01.170
So that hopefully you remember
enough from the other papers

01:14:01.170 --> 01:14:06.030
that we covered to kind of
imagine how one would fill this

01:14:06.030 --> 01:14:09.570
out, and we're actually at
these calibrated values--

01:14:09.570 --> 01:14:12.720
we're actually
matching quite well

01:14:12.720 --> 01:14:20.050
all the income shares for wages,
manufacturing, and agriculture.

01:14:20.050 --> 01:14:22.230
Yep?

01:14:22.230 --> 01:14:25.700
AUDIENCE: I might
remember wrong, but just--

01:14:25.700 --> 01:14:29.520
yeah, it's very likely,
but in your paper

01:14:29.520 --> 01:14:32.157
with Kaboski on the Million--

01:14:32.157 --> 01:14:33.490
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Baht Fund, yes.

01:14:36.050 --> 01:14:38.180
AUDIENCE: Is it
the interest rate

01:14:38.180 --> 01:14:44.510
wasn't going to be with
the intervention, was it?

01:14:44.510 --> 01:14:47.160
Now you just said that
the interest rate drop has

01:14:47.160 --> 01:14:49.410
to do with the Million Baht--

01:14:49.410 --> 01:14:51.460
ROBERT TOWNSEND:
Remember, what we're doing

01:14:51.460 --> 01:14:53.760
is kind of a variation
in the cross-section

01:14:53.760 --> 01:14:57.610
as a function of the percentage
of households in the village.

01:14:57.610 --> 01:15:02.510
So the per-capita
treatment is we're

01:15:02.510 --> 01:15:05.310
seeing whether that has any
impact on the interest rate.

01:15:05.310 --> 01:15:08.230
What I showed you was the time
variation in the interest rate,

01:15:08.230 --> 01:15:09.660
so it's a very different object.

01:15:09.660 --> 01:15:10.310
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:15:10.310 --> 01:15:11.227
ROBERT TOWNSEND: Yeah.

01:15:11.227 --> 01:15:13.830
So that's kind of like
differenced out, basically.

01:15:13.830 --> 01:15:18.095
It's the relative
difference from the trend

01:15:18.095 --> 01:15:19.470
and whether the
Million Baht Fund

01:15:19.470 --> 01:15:20.637
had something to do with it.

01:15:23.260 --> 01:15:23.760
OK.

01:15:23.760 --> 01:15:27.240
The last thing is flow of funds.

01:15:27.240 --> 01:15:30.270
These are the flow of funds
accounts for Thailand,

01:15:30.270 --> 01:15:31.080
basically.

01:15:34.490 --> 01:15:37.180
A quick introduction
to flow of funds,

01:15:37.180 --> 01:15:39.240
you've got non-financial
corporations,

01:15:39.240 --> 01:15:43.650
financial corporations,
government, households,

01:15:43.650 --> 01:15:47.620
and not-for-profit corporations,
and the rest of the world.

01:15:47.620 --> 01:15:49.320
Those are the sectors.

01:15:49.320 --> 01:15:53.640
And then you have
acquisition of assets,

01:15:53.640 --> 01:15:57.870
and they're actually in
detailed financial accounts.

01:15:57.870 --> 01:16:00.370
When the flow of funds
accounts-- when they exist,

01:16:00.370 --> 01:16:03.330
you've got money and
gold and currency,

01:16:03.330 --> 01:16:06.130
securities, loans, and so on.

01:16:06.130 --> 01:16:10.500
So acquiring a loan means
basically you're a lender.

01:16:10.500 --> 01:16:13.800
On the other hand, you've
got sort of liabilities

01:16:13.800 --> 01:16:16.890
down here, and so that you can
have a loan which represents

01:16:16.890 --> 01:16:19.140
an increase in borrowing.

01:16:19.140 --> 01:16:22.560
It takes a lot of concentration
to constantly remember

01:16:22.560 --> 01:16:25.500
uses means putting money--

01:16:25.500 --> 01:16:27.000
so the idea is you run--

01:16:29.530 --> 01:16:34.630
you have positive savings,
where do you put your money?

01:16:34.630 --> 01:16:36.640
And you could put it
here or you could reduce

01:16:36.640 --> 01:16:39.700
your deficits, or if you--

01:16:39.700 --> 01:16:40.720
reduce your liabilities.

01:16:40.720 --> 01:16:42.362
If you run it the
other way and you

01:16:42.362 --> 01:16:43.820
have negative
savings or something,

01:16:43.820 --> 01:16:45.820
and then you've got to
increase your liabilities

01:16:45.820 --> 01:16:49.880
or run down and sell off
some assets that you own.

01:16:49.880 --> 01:16:52.980
These are the
traditional labor labels

01:16:52.980 --> 01:16:55.075
in the flow of funds by sector.

01:16:58.150 --> 01:16:59.980
Is there a relationship
between flow

01:16:59.980 --> 01:17:02.080
of funds and the
national income accounts?

01:17:02.080 --> 01:17:03.250
Yes.

01:17:03.250 --> 01:17:06.460
Actually, in principle,
they should all

01:17:06.460 --> 01:17:09.280
be consistent with one another.

01:17:09.280 --> 01:17:11.740
But they're often not.

01:17:11.740 --> 01:17:15.010
The thing that is most
consistent is flow of funds

01:17:15.010 --> 01:17:18.010
into and out of the
financial institutions

01:17:18.010 --> 01:17:21.880
because commercial banks and
other financial corporations

01:17:21.880 --> 01:17:24.370
are required to
report to regulators,

01:17:24.370 --> 01:17:26.990
and the central bank
keeps track of things.

01:17:26.990 --> 01:17:31.480
So we see most accurately
deposits coming in,

01:17:31.480 --> 01:17:34.720
loans going out for
financial corporations.

01:17:34.720 --> 01:17:38.230
We often see little or
anything of the transactions

01:17:38.230 --> 01:17:41.170
between the other sectors.

01:17:41.170 --> 01:17:42.970
There are national
income and product

01:17:42.970 --> 01:17:48.880
account for those sectors,
and we see, therefore, savings

01:17:48.880 --> 01:17:52.660
for those, but those
savings numbers

01:17:52.660 --> 01:17:56.470
are often radically
different from the savings

01:17:56.470 --> 01:18:00.640
we would impute from
just seeing transactions

01:18:00.640 --> 01:18:03.190
with the measured
formal financial sector.

01:18:03.190 --> 01:18:05.620
Another way to say
this, if you read Deaton

01:18:05.620 --> 01:18:12.100
and so on, the savings you see
coming from household surveys

01:18:12.100 --> 01:18:14.860
gives you very, very different
numbers than the savings

01:18:14.860 --> 01:18:18.310
you'll see at the level of
the national income accounts,

01:18:18.310 --> 01:18:21.220
and that's because the
measurement is missing,

01:18:21.220 --> 01:18:26.030
so households get treated as the
residual in the national income

01:18:26.030 --> 01:18:26.530
accounts.

01:18:30.050 --> 01:18:35.990
But flow of funds data do
exist, and to some extent,

01:18:35.990 --> 01:18:40.820
they can be created, and
Thailand is, for example--

01:18:40.820 --> 01:18:46.310
and Mexico-- creating improved
financial flow of funds

01:18:46.310 --> 01:18:48.080
accounts.

01:18:48.080 --> 01:18:50.210
I'd like to think we had
something to do with that.

01:18:54.170 --> 01:18:55.880
We can also do it at
the village level.

01:18:55.880 --> 01:19:01.160
I've shown you a lot, but
let me just jump here.

01:19:04.700 --> 01:19:06.860
At the national
aggregate level, these

01:19:06.860 --> 01:19:10.220
are the traditional sectors,
and here's a diamond,

01:19:10.220 --> 01:19:15.890
and basically you can see
from the standpoint of banks,

01:19:15.890 --> 01:19:19.990
households are
interior-- basically

01:19:19.990 --> 01:19:22.010
households are
investing in banks,

01:19:22.010 --> 01:19:24.400
but that's a liability
for the banking sector.

01:19:24.400 --> 01:19:29.300
Savings accounts
are to be paid back.

01:19:29.300 --> 01:19:32.620
On the other hand, in this
period between '08 and--

01:19:32.620 --> 01:19:37.090
'04 and '08, you know the
banking sector was investing

01:19:37.090 --> 01:19:39.610
in the rest of the world and
that had to do with Thailand

01:19:39.610 --> 01:19:41.965
running a balance
of payments surplus.

01:19:44.660 --> 01:19:47.160
But this is at
the village level.

01:19:47.160 --> 01:19:51.200
And here, you can distinguish
financial corporations,

01:19:51.200 --> 01:19:54.680
transactions with businesses
outside the village,

01:19:54.680 --> 01:19:57.230
transactions of the village
funds we just talked about,

01:19:57.230 --> 01:20:01.310
and you can see them using
currency, running surpluses

01:20:01.310 --> 01:20:04.460
or deficits with these
other entities in terms

01:20:04.460 --> 01:20:06.020
of the objects.

01:20:06.020 --> 01:20:10.010
So the point here is that
it's a common way of measuring

01:20:10.010 --> 01:20:14.120
and it doesn't just have to be
applied as it is conventionally

01:20:14.120 --> 01:20:15.650
at the national level.

01:20:15.650 --> 01:20:19.430
Flow of funds can zoom
in and zoom out by region

01:20:19.430 --> 01:20:23.040
and tell you which object's
moving around over time.

01:20:23.040 --> 01:20:32.240
And in fact, you can read
it in a little more leisure

01:20:32.240 --> 01:20:37.460
style on your own, there's
papers of Guerrieri and Guido

01:20:37.460 --> 01:20:42.470
Lorenzoni and Monika Piazzesi
and Martin Schneider,

01:20:42.470 --> 01:20:46.160
and these are,
granted, about the US,

01:20:46.160 --> 01:20:49.910
but it's basically looking
at the household sector

01:20:49.910 --> 01:20:52.100
and going to the flow
of funds data in the US

01:20:52.100 --> 01:20:58.550
to measure changes in
savings and borrowing.

01:20:58.550 --> 01:21:01.400
And this same
language that they use

01:21:01.400 --> 01:21:03.890
to try to understand
what happens

01:21:03.890 --> 01:21:07.310
in a financial crisis
when all of a sudden you

01:21:07.310 --> 01:21:11.690
can't borrow as much
because the banks are tight,

01:21:11.690 --> 01:21:15.300
or in Monika's case, what
happens when there are many,

01:21:15.300 --> 01:21:19.080
many more young people
entering and they have

01:21:19.080 --> 01:21:21.860
certain expectations
about inflation,

01:21:21.860 --> 01:21:25.080
and each one of these
pairs of authors

01:21:25.080 --> 01:21:29.460
is doing this kind of experiment
in the context of a model.

01:21:29.460 --> 01:21:32.430
So these very same
models that rely

01:21:32.430 --> 01:21:35.370
on a sort of macro-aggregate
looking, though,

01:21:35.370 --> 01:21:40.500
at sectors in the US also
apply to developing countries.

01:21:40.500 --> 01:21:44.250
In fact Guido's model is eerily
similar, although none of us

01:21:44.250 --> 01:21:47.610
recognized it at the time, to
the model that Joe and I used

01:21:47.610 --> 01:21:52.730
to analyze the village
fund in in Thailand.